==Pre-race favorites==

Reigning champion [[Roberto Visentini]] returned to the race in 1987 to defend his crown,<ref name="elm DBPV">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/21/MD19870521-030.pdf|title=Visentini-Roche: Duelo "Fratricida"|language=Spanish|date=21 May 1987|page=30|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Visentini-Roche: Duel "Fratricide"|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQhtRsQq|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> despite not winning many races in his spring campaign.<ref name="BRI 87"/> [[Francesco Moser]], who won in [[1984 Giro d'Italia|1984]] and finished in the top three in [[1985 Giro d'Italia|1985]] and [[1986 Giro d'Italia|1986]], did not participate because of a head trauma and bruises sustained in a crash in the weeks prior to the race.<ref name="LA DBPV"/><ref name="Unita Pview"/><ref name="ep pview">{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/05/21/deportes/548546413_850215.html|title=Moser, sin recuperarse de su ca<U+00ED>da del lunes, ausente del Giro que se inicia hoy|language=Spanish|date=21 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Moser, reeling from its fall on Monday, absent the Tour that begins today|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QWhIpVFZ|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Spanish sports newspaper ''[[El Mundo Deportivo (newspaper)|El Mundo Deportivo]]'' and Gian Paolo Ormezzano from Italy's ''[[La Stampa]]'' named several other riders as contenders for the overall classification, such as [[Giuseppe Saronni]], then-[[UCI Road World Championships <U+2013> Men's road race|world champion]] [[Moreno Argentin]], [[Stephen Roche]], and [[Robert Millar]].<ref name="LA DBPV"/><ref name="elm DBPV"/> Since {{ct|LVC|1987}} team leader [[Greg LeMond]] did not participate in the race due to injuries sustained in a [[Greg LeMond#1987.E2.80.931988: Accidental shooting.2C lost years|hunting accident]],<ref name="av"/> ''El Mundo Deportivo'' believed [[Jean-Fran<U+00E7>ois Bernard]] to be a dark horse.<ref name="elm DBPV"/><ref name="av">{{cite news|author=Jean Montois|url=http://streaming.ajgirona.org/pandora/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?xslt=show_pdf;publication=Avui;sort_publication=avui;day=21;month=05;year=1987;page=036;id=0002854626;filename=19870521;collection=pages;url_high=pages/Avui/1987/198705/19870521/19870521036.pdf|title=Roche i Visentini, favorits en les apostes del Giro d'Italia|language=Spanish|date=21 June 1987|newspaper=Avui|publisher=Hermes Comunicacions S.A.|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Roche and Visentini, betting favorites in the Tour of Italy|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140629163217/http://streaming.ajgirona.org/pandora/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?xslt=show_pdf;publication=Avui;sort_publication=avui;day=21;month=05;year=1987;page=036;id=0002854626;filename=19870521;collection=pages;url_high=pages/Avui/1987/198705/19870521/19870521036.pdf|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> ''[[L'Unit<U+00E0>]]'' writer Gino Sala believed Roche, Saronni, and Visentini were the top three challengers for the overall crown,<ref name="Unita Pview"/> while Ormezzano considered that Argentin, [[Guido Bontempi]], [[Urs Freuler]], and [[Paolo Rosola]] all had a great chance to win a stage in the race.<ref name="LA DBPV"/> Mario Fossati of ''[[La Repubblica]]'' also thought that Bernard, Bontempi, and [[Phil Anderson (cyclist)|Phil Anderson]] could take a stage win.<ref name="LR B4">{{cite web|author=Mario Fossati|language=Italian|date=19 May 1987|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1987/05/19/sognando-un-giro-altri-tempi.html?ref=search|title=Sognando Un Giro d'Altri Tempi|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso| accessdate= 25 June 2014 | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QbiGcXr1|page=45| archivedate= 24 June 2014| deadurl= no|trans_title=Dreaming A Giro of Other Times}}</ref> 

There was a strong belief that the race would be a battle between Carrera Jeans-Vagabond teammates Visentini and Roche.<ref name="LA DBPV"/><ref name="elm DBPV"/> ''El Mundo Deportivo'' stated that Visentini had the edge in the time trial discipline and sprinting, while Roche had the advantage in climbing mountains.<ref name="elm DBPV"/> However, unlike Visentini, Roche came into the race in great shape after winning the [[Tour de Romandie]] and placing second in the [[Li<U+00E8>ge-Bastogne-Li<U+00E8>ge]] and the [[Crit<U+00E9>rium International]].<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="elm DBPV"/><ref name="ep pview"/> Cycling expert and author Bill McGann thought that the race would be disputed between Visentini and [[Gianbattista Baronchelli]].<ref name="BRI 87"/>

== Route and stages ==

[[File:Terminillo.JPG|right|thumb|[[Monte Terminillo]] hosted the end of the {{convert|134|km|0|abbr=on}} sixth stage and the start of the {{convert|205|km|0|abbr=on}} seventh stage.|alt=A mountain in the distance.]]
The route for the 1987 edition of the Giro d'Italia was revealed to the public on television by head organizer Vincenzo Torriani on 21 February 1987.<ref name="LA unveil1">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,21/articleid,0970_01_1987_0045_0039_23440494/|title=La Vall<U+00E9>e in maglia rosa|language=Italian|date=22 February 1987|page=21|newspaper=La Stampa|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=22 June 2012|format=|trans_title=Pink Jersey in the Valley}}</ref><ref name="LA unveil2">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,21/articleid,0970_01_1987_0045_0052_23442100/|title=Tre giorni a Sanremo con il <<Giro d'Italia>>|language=Italian|date=22 February 1987|page=21|newspaper=La Stampa|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=22 June 2012|format=|trans_title=Three Days in Sanremo with the <<Tour of Italy>>}}</ref><ref name="elm unveil">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/02/22/MD19870222-041.pdf|title=Se Presento El Giro - 87|language=Spanish|date=22 February 1987|page=41|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=The Giro Presented - 87|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQhyOsLh|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Covering a total of {{convert|3915|km|abbr=on}}, it included five time trials (four [[individual time trial|individual]] and one for [[team time trial|teams]]),<ref name="elm unveil"/> and thirteen stages with categorized climbs that awarded [[Mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|mountains classification]] points. Five of these thirteen stages had summit finishes: stage 1a, to San Romolo;<ref name="elm prologue review & stage 1a &1b preview">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/22/MD19870522-027.pdf|title=Visentini Empalmo El Rosa|language=Spanish|date=22 May 1987|page=27|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Visentini splices the rosa|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQi0W3VB|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm route source">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/21/MD19870521-031.pdf|title=Etapas, Puertos Y Kilometrajes|language=Spanish|date=21 May 1987|page=31|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Stages, Ports and riding distances|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQi2UgiF|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> stage 6, to [[Monte Terminillo]];<ref name="elm route source"/> stage 15, to [[Sappada]];<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="CW 1987 GTD">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/grand-tour-doubles-stephen-roche-126343|title=Grand Tour Doubles <U+2013> Stephen Roche|date=16 July 1987|work=Cycling Weekly|publisher=IPC Media Limited|accessdate=17 July 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQi4XFr2|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> stage 19, to [[Madesimo]];<ref name="elm route source"/> and stage 21, to [[Pila, Aosta Valley|Pila]].<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="elm route source"/><ref name="EPunt pview">{{cite news|url=http://streaming.ajgirona.org/pandora/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?xslt=show_pdf;publication=Sitios%20de%20Gerona,%20Los;sort_publication=sitios.de.gerona.los;day=21;month=05;year=1987;page=024;id=0002644152;filename=19870521;collection=pages;url_high=pages/Sitios%20de%20Gerona,%20Los/1987/198705/19870521/19870521024.pdf|title=Pere Mu<U+00F1>oz, ante su primer gran <<test>> de la temporada|language=Spanish|date=21 May 1987|page=24|newspaper=El Punt|publisher=Hermes Comunicacions S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Pere Mu<U+00F1>oz, before his first big test of the season|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140626011318/http://streaming.ajgirona.org/pandora/cgi-bin/Pandora.exe?xslt=show_pdf;publication=Sitios%20de%20Gerona,%20Los;sort_publication=sitios.de.gerona.los;day=21;month=05;year=1987;page=024;id=0002644152;filename=19870521;collection=pages;url_high=pages/Sitios%20de%20Gerona,%20Los/1987/198705/19870521/19870521024.pdf|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Another stage with a mountain-top finish was stage 13, which consisted of a climbing time trial to San Marino.<ref name="elm route source"/><ref name="EPunt pview"/> The organizers chose to include one rest day between stages 10 and 11.<ref name="BRI 87"/> When compared to the [[1986 Giro d'Italia|previous edition]], the race had the same amount of stages <U+2013> although one stage consisted of two half-stages <U+2013> but was {{convert|56.4|km|0|abbr=on}} longer and contained an additional individual time trial.<ref name="BRI 86">{{cite web|url=http://bikeraceinfo.com/giro/giro1986.html |title=1986 Giro d'Italia |work= Bike Race Info |publisher=Dog Ear Publishing |author=Bill and Carol McGann |accessdate=2012-08-06|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQi7Xcxu|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The sixteenth stage, which ran from Sappada to [[Canazei]], was named the [[Glossary of bicycling#Q|queen stage]] for its five categorized climbs.<ref name="EPunt pview"/><ref name="ep 15rv">{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/07/deportes/550015220_850215.html|author=J. Tolosa|title=Vuelco en el Giro, con Roche de nuevo l<U+00ED>der tras atacar a su compa<U+00F1>ero Visentini|language=Spanish|date=7 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Dump in the Giro, with Roche leading again after attacking his partner Visentini|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QWlHXkqI|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Race director Torriani was happy with the success the [[1985 Giro d'Italia]] had when passing through the [[Aosta Valley]] and chose to include this mountainous region, which lies adjacent to the [[Rh<U+00F4>ne-Alpes]], in the 1987 route.<ref name="LA unveil1"/> With the Giro's return to the valley, ''La Stampa'' and the regional cycling federation director, Maggiorino Ferrero, speculated that the stages taking place in this region would be critical in deciding the general classification. Carlo Champvillair, a climbing champion of Aosta Valley, believed it to be a well-constructed, technical race route.<ref name="LA unveil1"/> The time trial in San Marino, the sixth stage with the finish atop Monte Terminillo, and the stages including the [[Dolomites]] were seen by ''L'Unit<U+00E0>'' writer Gino Sala as stages that would heavily influence the general classification.<ref name="Unita Pview"/> In addition, he said that the route was suited to well-rounded, strong, and durable riders.<ref name="Unita Pview"/>

