==Race overview==
[[File:Moreno Argentin.jpg|upright|thumb|alt=A man on straddling a bike in sunglasses.|[[Moreno Argentin]] (pictured during the [[Coors Classic]] in 1987) won three individual stages at the 1987 Giro.]]
The Giro began with a {{convert|4|km|1|abbr=on}} prologue through the streets of San Remo. The returning winner of the Giro, Roberto Visentini, won the prologue by two tenths of a second over the Canadian rider [[Steve Bauer]].<ref name="CW Pto3 Recap">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest/346952/from-the-cw-archives-the-1987-giro-d-italia-part-1.html|title=From The CW Archives: The 1987 Giro d'Italia Part 1|date=28 May 2008|work=Cycling Weekly|publisher=IPC Media Limited|accessdate=27 May 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiFGWKj|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The next race day held two stages: a {{convert|31|km|1|abbr=on}} stage with a summit finish, followed by a downhill individual time trial.<ref name="CW Pto3 Recap"/> {{ct|Panasonic|1987}}'s [[Erik Breukink]] took the climbing half-stage win with a solo attack.<ref name="elm stage 1a & 1b review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/23/MD19870523-035.pdf|title=Breukink, Un Recien Llegado Al Trono Rosa|language=Spanish|date=23 May 1987|page=35|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Breukink, a newcomer to the rosa throne|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiIn0e4|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> His performance earned him the race leader's ''maglia rosa'' ({{lang-en|[[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|pink jersey]]}}),<ref name="CW Pto3 Recap"/> which he kept until the third stage. Stephen Roche won the time trial half-stage with a three-second margin over [[Del Tongo]]'s [[Lech Piasecki]].<ref name="BRI 87"/> [[Johan van der Velde]] formed a lead group with about {{convert|30|km|1|abbr=on}} to go in the second stage, but as he posed a threat to the race lead, he was not given a large advantage and was subsequently caught by the chasing peloton {{convert|7|km|1|abbr=on}} from the finish.<ref name="CW Pto3 Recap"/> The main field remained intact for the remaining kilometers and the race geared up for a sprint finish won by Moreno Argentin.<ref name="CW Pto3 Recap"/>

The third stage was a lengthy team time trial that stretched for {{convert|43|km|1|abbr=on}} between [[Lerici]] and [[Camaiore]]. {{ct|CAR|1987}} beat out the Del Tongo squad by fifty-four seconds to win the leg. In addition to the stage victory, Carrera Jeans-Vagabond's Roche took the overall lead.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="CW 1987 GTD"/> As the leading group approached the fourth stage finish line, Argentin sprinted away with {{convert|800|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} to go and created a two-second gap between himself and the rider in second place that was enough to earn him a second stage win.<ref>{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/05/26/deportes/548978403_850215.html|title=Triunfo del campe<U+00F3>n mundial, Argentin, en la cuarta etapa del Giro|language=Spanish|date=26 May 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Triumph of the world champion, Argentin, in the fourth stage of Giro|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QZbpsiyZ|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="CW 4to8 Recap">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest/346951/from-the-cw-archives-the-1987-giro-d-italia-part-2.html|title=From The CW Archives: The 1987 Giro d'Italia Part 2|date=28 May 2008|page=|work=Cycling Weekly|publisher=IPC Media Limited|accessdate=27 May 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiL9IpP|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The fifth stage was relatively flat and was used to set up the race to enter the [[Apennine mountains]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/05/27/deportes/549064807_850215.html|title=El Giro llega a su primera jornada monta<U+00F1>osa|language=Spanish|date=27 May 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=The Giro reaches its first mountain day|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QZcDg0z2|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The leg culminated in a mass sprint that was won by Panasonic-Isostar's Belgian rider [[Eddy Planckaert]], after overcoming Paolo Rosola in the closing meters.<ref name="CW 4to8 Recap"/><ref name="elm stage 5 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/27/MD19870527-033.pdf|title=Primer Triunfo De Planckaert en el Giro|language=Spanish|date=27 May 1987|page=33|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Planckaert First Win in Giro|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiO2fvv|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Roche defended his race lead until stage thirteen, a {{convert|46|km|1|abbr=on}} climbing individual time trial to [[Monte Titano]] in [[San Marino]],<ref>{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/05/deportes/549842414_850215.html|title=Visentini, nuevo l<U+00ED>der del Giro, tras ganar en San Marino|language=Spanish|date=5 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Visentini, new leader of the Tour, after winning in San Marino|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QaJKGN5r|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> where he lost the pink jersey to his teammate and stage winner Visentini.<ref name="elm stage 13 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/05/MD19870605-045.pdf|title=Visentini: La Contrarreloj Consagra|language=Spanish|date=5 June 1987|page=43|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Visentini: The Time Trial consecrates|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiPpt2e|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Roche claimed his performance in the stage was hampered due to injuries sustained from a crash in the tenth stage.<ref name="CW 10to15 Recap">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest/346950/from-the-cw-archives-the-1987-giro-d-italia-part-3.html|title=From The CW Archives: The 1987 Giro d'Italia Part 3|date=28 May 2008|page=|work=Cycling Weekly|publisher=IPC Media Limited|accessdate=27 May 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiR65xT|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> At {{convert|260|km|1|abbr=on}}, the fourteenth stage was the longest of the race. It was won in a mass sprint by [[Fanini-Maggi Mobili|Remac Fanini]]'s [[Paolo Cimini]], who overtook Rosola in the final meters.<ref name="CW 10to15 Recap"/><ref name="EP 14">{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/06/deportes/549928813_850215.html|title=Triunfo al 'sprint' de Cimini en la etapa m<U+00E1>s larga del Giro|language=Spanish|date=6 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Triumph to sprint Cimini on the longest stage of the Giro|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QaJfae8L|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

[[File:San Marino 010.jpg|left|thumb|alt=An overhead picture of a city.|[[San Marino]] hosted the end of the stage 13 individual time trial, as well as the start of the {{convert|260|km|1|abbr=on}} fourteenth stage.]]
The fifteenth stage saw the race enter the Dolomites and traverse three major climbs within the mountain chain.<ref name="BRI 87"/> On the descent of the Monte Rest, Roche formed a leading group with two other riders after speeding away from the race leader's group. Despite orders from his team management, Roche continued with the move.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="LR Hist">{{cite web|author=Eugenio Capodacqua|language=Italian|date=10 May 2007|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/05/speciale/altri/2007giroditalia/storia-3/storia-3.html|title=La storia del Giro d'Italia|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso| accessdate= 27 December 2007 | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20071224103726/http://www.repubblica.it/2007/05/speciale/altri/2007giroditalia/storia-3/storia-3.html| archivedate= 24 December 2007| deadurl= no|trans_title=The history of the Tour of Italy}}</ref> The Carrera Jeans-Vagabond pack chased after the Roche group to protect the advantage of Roche's teammate and race leader Visentini.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="CW 1987 GTD"/> Roche crossed the finish line in twelfth place, fifty-six seconds after the stage winner van der Velde, which allowed him to don again the pink jersey by five seconds over [[Tony Rominger]].<ref name="CW 10to15 Recap"/><ref name="elm stage 15 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/07/MD19870607-051.pdf|title=Roche, De Rosa; Lejarreta, Con El "Giro" A Su Alcance|language=Spanish|date=7 June 1987|page=51|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Roche, in Rose; Lejarreta, with the Giro within reach|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiWBiVU|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Roche's actions, taking the race lead away from Visentini and disobeying team commands, gained him the hatred of the the Italian cyclings fans.<ref name="glory">{{cite news|url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/tourdefrance2007/story/0,,2118236,00.html|title=Roche remembers his annus mirabilis|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=20 July 2007 | location=London | first=Paul | last=Doyle | date=5 July 2007|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiXmLUw|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The sixteenth leg of the race included five categorized climbs before concluding in the municipality of Canazei.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap">{{cite news|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest/346949/from-the-cw-archives-the-1987-giro-d-italia-part-4.html|title=From The CW Archives: The 1987 Giro d'Italia Part 4|date=28 May 2008|page=|work=Cycling Weekly|publisher=IPC Media Limited|accessdate=27 May 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQic1ovr|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm stage 16 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/08/MD19870608-055.pdf|title=La Crisis Entre Las Figuras Have Temblar El "Giro"|language=Spanish|date=8 June 1987|page=55|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Crisis Between the Figures Have Shaken The "Giro"|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiZzvd6|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> On the descent of the [[Passo Pordoi|Pordoi Pass]], van der Velde broke away and caught up to the leader on the road before winning his second consecutive stage.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/> Meanwhile, behind van der Velde, Visentini tried several times to attack Roche on the slopes of the [[Passo Fedaia]]; however, Roche marked all of his moves and the two raced to the finish in the same group.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/> Stage 17, the race's final day in the Dolomites,<ref name="BRI 87"/> was marred by poor weather. A breakaway group of three was given a significant gap as the main general classification contenders rode behind in a collective group.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 17">{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/09/deportes/550188015_850215.html|title=Triunfo de Vitali en la 17<U+00AA> etapa del Giro|language=Spanish|date=9 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Vitali triumph in the 17th stage of the Giro |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QaOLr3bQ|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Atala (cycling team)|Atala Ofmega]]'s Italian rider [[Marco Vitali]] out-sprinted his two fellow breakaway members to win his first Grand Tour stage win.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 17"/><ref name="elm stage 17 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/09/MD19870609-037.pdf|title=Vitali Se Aprovecho De La Tregua Entre Roche Y Visentini|language=Spanish|date=9 June 1987|page=37|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Vitali took advantage of the truce between Roche and Visentini|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQifBgNO|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

As the eighteenth stage began, the peloton felt they deserved a rest day after three difficult stages in the Dolomites and collectively rode at a non-aggressive pace for over three-quarters of the stage.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 18">{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/10/deportes/550274415_850215.html|title=Lenta etapa en el Giro como protesta por no haber Jornada de descanso|date=10 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Slow Giro stage protest for failing Day off |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QaPLPH5U|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="LR 18">{{cite web|author=Mario Fossati|language=Italian|date=10 June 1987|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1987/06/10/un-giorno-di-cicloturismo.html?ref=search|title=Un Giorno di Cicloturismo|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso| accessdate= 27 December 2007 | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QaPUiTwZ |page=36| archivedate= 24 June 2014| deadurl= no|trans_title=A Day of Cycling}}</ref> Riders began to attack and form breakaway groups with about {{convert|30|km|1|abbr=on}} to go; however, the sprinters' teams reeled in all attacks and prepared for a sprint finish that was eventually won by [[Giuseppe Calcaterra]], making it the second consecutive stage win for Atala-Ofmega.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 18"/><ref name="LR 18"/> During the nineteenth stage, Jean-Fran<U+00E7>ois Bernard launched an attack after the leading group finished the climb of the [[San Marco Pass]].<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/> Three riders joined Bernard before the start of the final climb in Madesimo, but Bernard dropped them early on in the climb and rode the final {{convert|18|km|1|abbr=on}} alone to win the stage. Millar and [[Marino Lejarreta]] managed to gain over thirty seconds on Roche after they attacked on the final climb.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="elm stage 19 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/11/MD19870611-034.pdf|title=Bernard Hizo Honor A Su "Padre Espiritual"|language=Spanish|date=11 June 1987|page=34|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Bernard lived up to his "spiritual father"|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQijkYPz|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Despite a crash within the final kilometer of stage twenty, the main field managed to hold a bunch sprint that was won by Rosola.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref>{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/12/deportes/550447211_850215.html|title=Rosola gan<U+00F3> la <U+00FA>ltima etapa llana en el Giro|date=12 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Rosola won the last flat stage in Giro|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Qazvrdsa|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

[[File:Robert MILLAR (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|alt=A picture of a cyclist wearing a helmet.|By winning the twenty-first stage, [[Robert Millar]] (pictured here on the [[Tour de France]] in [[1993 Tour de France|1993]]) vaulted to second overall.]]
In the twenty-first leg, the general classification contenders were a part of the same leading group until the final climb to the summit finish in Pila.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 21">{{cite news|author= J. Tolosa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1987/06/13/deportes/550533605_850215.html|title=Roche, virtual ganador del Giro pese al ataque de Lejarreta|date=13 June 1987|newspaper= El Pa<U+00ED>s|publisher=Ediciones El Pa<U+00ED>s|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Roche, virtual Giro winner despite the attack Lejarreta |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Qb0RSckK|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Lejarreta attacked {{convert|12|km|1|abbr=on}} from the finish and only seven other riders were able to mark, including Millar and Roche. Over {{convert|6|km|1|abbr=on}} later, the Spaniard attacked again and only Roche and Millar remained with him. Despite further attacks by Lejarreta, the group rode together up to the finish. With over {{convert|300|m|1|abbr=on}} to go, Millar unleashed a sprint that won him the stage.<ref name="EP 21"/> Millar's performance on the stay brought him to second place overall.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/><ref name="EP 21"/> The final stage of the 1987 Giro d'Italia was a {{convert|32|km|1|abbr=on}} individual time trial.<ref name="CW 1987 GTD"/> Visentini, who had crashed in the previous stage, did not start and abandoned the race.<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/> Roche beat out the second place finisher, Dietrich Thurau, by fourteen seconds to win the day and the overall race itself.<ref name="Unita S22 Results">{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.unita.it/cgi-bin/highlightPdf.cgi?t=ebook&file=/archivio/uni_1987_06/19870614_0023.pdf&query=|title=Roche, il nome della rosa|language=Italian|date=14 June 1987|page=23|newspaper=l'Unit<U+00E0>|publisher=PCI |accessdate=22 June 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Roche, the name of the rosa|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQilNK9k|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> In doing so, Roche became the first Irishman to win the Giro d'Italia.<ref name="ELM S22 Results">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/14/MD19870614-041.pdf|title=B... Roche De Oro|language=Spanish|date=14 June 1987|page=41|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Golden Roche|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQhke1tv|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="Stampa S22 Reslts n PR">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,0027/articleid,0975_01_1987_0138_0059_23892283/|title=Stop al Giro targato Roche|language=Italian|date=14 June 1987|page=27|newspaper=La Stampa|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=22 June 2012|format=|trans_title=Stop at the Giro branded Roche}}</ref> The other podium positions were filled by non-Italian riders for the second time in the history of the race.<ref name="ELM S22 Results"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Andrea Tabacco|url=http://it.eurosport.yahoo.com/28052012/45/giro-d-italia-hesjedal-vince-giro-scarponi.html|title=Giro d'Italia <U+2013> Hesjedal vince il Giro: Scarponi <U+00E8> quarto|language=Italian|work=Yahoo! Eurosport|publisher=Yahoo! e Eurosport|date=27 May 2012|accessdate=24 June 2013|trans_title=Tour of Italy <U+2013> Hesjedal wins the Tour: Scarponi is fourth|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QP3px6zy|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Four riders achieved multiple stage victories: Argentin (stages 2, 4, and 7),<ref name="elm stage 2 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/24/MD19870524-043.pdf|title=Argentin, A Lo Campeon|language=Spanish|date=24 May 1987|page=43|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Argentin, To The Champion|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiplz5R|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm stage 4 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/26/MD19870526-031.pdf|title=Argentin, Segundo Podio Del "Giro"|language=Spanish|date=26 May 1987|page=31|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Argentin, Second podium of the "Giro"|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQirklL0|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm stage 7 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/29/MD19870529-043.pdf|title=Trio De Victorias Para Argentin|language=Spanish|date=29 May 1987|page=43|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Trio of wins for Argentin|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQitEdrR|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Rosola (stages 8, 10, and 20),<ref name="elm stage 8 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/30/MD19870530-039.pdf|title="Lancia Pagnin" Volvio A Escaparse|language=Spanish|date=30 May 1987|page=39|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title="Lancia Pagnin" escaped again|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiv32Ya|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm stage 20 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/12/MD19870612-037.pdf|title=Hoy Se La Juega Marino Lejarreta|language=Spanish|date=12 June 1987|page=37|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Today is The Play for Marino Lejarreta|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiwgPkE|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Visentini (prologue and stage 13),<ref name="elm prologue review & stage 1a &1b preview"/><ref name="elm stage 13 review"/> and Roche (stages 1b and 22).<ref name="elm stage 1a & 1b review"/><ref name="Unita S22 Results"/> Stage wins were achieved by seven of the twenty competing squads, five of which won multiple stages. Gewiss-Bianchi collected a total of six stage wins through two riders, Argentin and Rosola. Carrera Jeans-Vagabond achieved the same feat with individual stage wins from Bontempi (stage 12),<ref name="elm stage 12 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/04/MD19870604-043.pdf|title=Bontempi Se Vengo De Las Criticas|language=Spanish|date=4 June 1987|page=43|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Bontempi avenges the criticism|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQiyeHOZ|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Roche and Visentini (two wins each), and a team time trial win (stage 3).<ref name="elm stage 3 review"/> Panasonic-Isostar amassed a total of three stage victories through Breukink (stage 1a),<ref name="elm stage 1a & 1b review"/> Planckaert (stage 5),<ref name="elm stage 5 review"/> and Millar (stage 21).<ref name="elm stage 21 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/13/MD19870613-035.pdf|title=Lejarreta, Fenomeno En La Ultima Monta<U+00F1>a|language=Spanish|date=13 June 1987|page=35|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Lejarreta, Phenomenon on the Last Mountain|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQj0MLK1|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Atala-Ofmega also secured three stage wins, through Freuler (stage 9),<ref name="elm stage 9 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/31/MD19870531-045.pdf|title=El "Sprint" De Freuler, Lo Mejor De Una Aburrida Etapa|language=Spanish|date=31 May 1987|page=45|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=The "Sprint" to Freuler, Best of a boring stage|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQj2FRrx|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Vitali (stage 17),<ref name="elm stage 17 review"/> and Calcaterra (stage 18).<ref name="elm stage 18 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/10/MD19870610-037.pdf|title=Calcaterra, En La Etapa De "Descanso"|language=Spanish|date=10 June 1987|page=37|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Calcaterra wins the stage of rest|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQih2d6A|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Gis Gelati-Jollyscarpe won two stages with van der Velde (stages 15 and 16).<ref name="elm stage 15 review"/><ref name="elm stage 16 review"/> Fagor-MBK also collected two stage successes, with [[Jean-Claude Bagot]] (stage 6) and [[Robert Forest (cyclist)|Robert Forest]] (stage 11).<ref name="elm stage 6 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/05/28/MD19870528-039.pdf|title=Roche Y Visentini Hacen Seleccion En La Monta<U+00F1>a|language=Spanish|date=28 May 1987|page=39|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Roche and Visentini make the selection in the mountains|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQj3xIn6|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="elm stage 11 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/03/MD19870603-035.pdf|title=Forest Dio La Segunda Victoria a "Fagor"|language=Spanish|date=3 June 1987|page=35|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=The Second Victory for Forest of "Fagor"|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQj5cbDg|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Remac-Fanini and Toshiba-Look both won a single stage at the Giro, the first through Cimini (stage 14),<ref name="elm stage 14 review">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/06/06/MD19870606-043.pdf|title=Cimini Sorprendio A Los Sprinters En Una Autopista|language=Spanish|date=6 June 1987|page=43|newspaper=El Mundo Deportivo|publisher=El Mundo Deportivo S.A.|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans_title=Cimini surprised the Sprinters on a Highway|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQj7ou2w|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> and the second through Bernard (stage 19).<ref name="elm stage 19 review"/>

==Classification leadership==
[[File:Passo Pordoi 2007.jpg|left|thumb|alt=A picture of a mountain.|The [[Passo Pordoi|Pordoi Pass]] was the ''Cima Coppi'' for the 1987 running of the Giro d'Italia.]]
Four different jerseys were worn during the 1987 Giro d'Italia. The leader of the [[General classification in the Giro d'Italia|general classification]] <U+2013> calculated by adding the stage finish times of each rider, and allowing time bonuses for the first three finishers on mass-start stages <U+2013> wore a pink jersey. The time bonuses for the 1987 Giro were twenty seconds for the first place, fifteen seconds for the second place, ten seconds for the third place, and five seconds for the fourth place on the stage.<ref name="elm stage 5 review"/> This classification is the most important of the race, and its winner is considered to be the winner of the Giro.<ref name="demystified">{{cite web|author=Laura Weislo|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/road/2008/giro08/?id=/features/2008/giro_classifications08|title=Giro d'Italia classifications demystified|date=13 May 2008|work=Cycling News|publisher=Future Publishing Limited|accessdate=13 July 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QP4eTB2p|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

For the [[Points classification in the Giro d'Italia|points classification]], which awarded a purple (or [[cyclamen]]) jersey to its leader, cyclists were given points for finishing a stage in the top 15; additional points could also be won in intermediate sprints. The green jersey was awarded to the [[Mountains classification in the Giro d'Italia|mountains classification]] leader. In this ranking, points were won by reaching the summit of a climb ahead of other cyclists. Each climb was ranked as either first, second or third category, with more points available for higher category climbs. The ''[[Cima Coppi]]'', the race's highest point of elevation, awarded more points than the other first category climbs.<ref name="demystified"/> The ''Cima Coppi'' for this edition of the Giro was the [[Pordoi Pass|Passo Pordoi]],<ref name="ep pview"/><ref name="EPunt pview"/> and the first rider to cross it was Fagor-MBK's [[Jean-Claude Bagot]].<ref name="CW 16to22 Recap"/> The white jersey was worn by the leader of [[Young rider classification in the Giro d'Italia|young rider classification]], a ranking decided the same way as the general classification, but considering only neo-professional cyclists (in their first three years of professional racing).<ref name="ELM S22 Results"/><ref name="demystified" /> Although no jersey was awarded, there was also one classification for the teams, in which the stage finish times of the best three cyclists per team were added; the leading team was the one with the lowest total time.<ref name="demystified" />

