==Aftermath==
[[File:1987 Stephen Roche Giro TT.jpg|right|thumb|alt=A man on a bike in a cycling jersey.|[[Stephen Roche]] (pictured during the [[1987 Tour de France]]) won the Tour and the [[1987 UCI Road World Championships <U+2013> Men's road race|men's road race]] at the [[UCI Road World Championships]] in the same calendar year.]]
Upon completing the final stage, Roche told the media that by winning the final time trial he felt he silenced any critics who doubted whether he should have won the race.<ref name="ELM S22 Results"/> In addition, Roche announced his intention to compete in the [[1987 Tour de France|Tour de France]] in July.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="ELM S22 Results"/> He won the Tour with a margin of forty seconds over the second-place finisher and thus became the [[Grand Tour (cycling)#Winners of two Grand Tours in a year|fifth rider]] to win the Giro and Tour in the same year.{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=29}}<ref name="ELMTDF">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/07/27/MD19870727-038.pdf|title=Clasificaciones oficiales|date=27 July 1987|accessdate=31 March 2012|page=38|language=Spanish|work=El Mundo Deportivo|trans_title=Official Classifications|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQjCGHMd|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="SI Wolf">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1066242/index.htm|title=Score A Big One For The Irish|author=Alexander Wolff|date=3 August 1987|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Inc.|accessdate=15 May 2014|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQjFneuP|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> In September, Roche won the [[1987 UCI Road World Championships <U+2013> Men's road race|men's road race]] at the [[1987 UCI Road World Championships]] and became the second rider to achieve the [[Triple Crown of Cycling]], which consists of winning two [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]] races and the [[UCI Road World Championships <U+2013> Men's road race|men's road race]] at the [[UCI Road World Championships]] in a calendar year.{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=30}}<ref name="ELMWCRR">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD01/HEM/1987/09/07/MD19870907-048.pdf|title="De Roche" De Facultades|date=7 September 1987|accessdate=31 March 2012|page=48|language=Spanish|work=El Mundo Deportivo|trans_title="De Roche" of Schools|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQjHiH2F|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>{{sfn|Heijmans|Mallon|2011|p=130}} For his career successes in the Giro d'Italia, Roche was inducted into the race's Hall of Fame in 2014.<ref name="VN SR GDTHOF">{{cite news|author=Neal Rogers|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2014/02/news/stephen-roche-joins-giro-ditalia-hall-of-fame_318032|title=Stephen Roche joins Giro d'Italia Hall of Fame|date=25 February 2014 |work=VeloNews|publisher=Competitor Group, Inc|accessdate=14 May 2014|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QQjDmgKQ|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=RCS Sport Press Office|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Giroditalia/2014/en/26-02-2014/stephen-roche-the-giro-d-italia-hall-of-fame-80134498510.shtml|title=Stephen Roche in the Giro d'Italia Hall of Fame|date=26 February 2014 |work=La Gazzetta dello Sporta|publisher=RCS Sport|accessdate=14 May 2014|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QYj98wkR|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="ISXIX">{{cite news|url=http://www.ilsecoloxix.it/p/sport/2014/03/04/AQCjjAzB-visentini_lontano_ciclismo.shtml|title=Visentini: "Colpa di Roche se sono lontano dal ciclismo" |language=Italian|date=4 March 2014|work=Il Secolo XIX|publisher=Societ<U+00E0> Edizioni e Pubblicazioni|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Visentini: "Blame Roche
if they are away from cycling <U+00BB>|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140629164112/http://www.ilsecoloxix.it/p/sport/2014/03/04/AQCjjAzB-visentini_lontano_ciclismo.shtml|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> After dropping out of the 1987 edition of the Giro, Visentini did not win any further stages or classifications in major races,<ref name="BRI 87"/> and retired from cycling in 1990, at the age of 33.<ref name="ISXIX"/>

''La Repubblica'' stated that the Italian riders had the second worst performance in the history of the Giro after [[1972 Giro d'Italia|1972]], since none finished inside the top four and many famous Italian cyclists failed to complete the race.<ref name="LRFin">{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1987/06/14/solo-nel-72-gli-italiani-sono.html?ref=search|title=Solo nel '72 gli Italiani Sono Andati Cosi' Male&nbsp;... |language=Italian|date=14 June 1987|page=43|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Only '72 The Italians Are Gone As Bad&nbsp;... |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QYqAzlXG|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Mario Fossati, of ''La Repubblica'', thought that van der Velde and Bernard performed very strongly, along with Argentin, whom he said was operating on "[[alternating current]]."<ref name="LRFin2">{{cite news|author=Mario Fossati|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1987/06/16/bravo-roche-ma-chi-inseguiva.html?ref=search|title=Bravo Roche ma chi Inseguiva? |language=Italian|date=16 June 1987|page=27|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Bravo Roche but who chased?|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QYkINfBv|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Fossati also said that Cimini and Calcaterra could have promising careers, based on their efforts during the race.<ref name="LRFin2"/>

The 1987 Giro has become famous for the series of events involving teammates Roche and Visentini.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="glory"/><ref name="VN SR GDTHOF"/><ref name="SI Wolf"/> Many writers highlight the fifteenth stage as the defining moment of the race.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="LR Hist"/><ref name="glory"/><ref name="SI Wolf"/><ref name="VN SR GDTHOF"/><ref name="ISXIX"/><ref name="CDA15">{{cite news|url=http://corrierealpi.gelocal.it/sport/2011/05/08/news/lite-furiosa-fra-visentini-e-roche-1.963397|title=Lite furiosa fra Visentini e Roche |language=Italian|date=8 May 2011|newspaper=Corriere delle Alpi|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=Furious quarrel between Roche and Visentini|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org//6QYlYkQwc|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The ''Corriere delle Alpi'' and cycling book author Bill McGann even named it as one of the most famous in the Giro d'Italia and cycling history.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="CDA15"/> On that day, Roche &ndash; who was second in the general classification and over two minutes behind race leader Visentini &ndash; attacked the lead, despite orders from his team to stop.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="SI Wolf"/><ref name="VN SR GDTHOF"/>{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=26}} Upon completing the stage, Visentini told the press that either Roche or himself would not start the following day,<ref name="ep 15rv"/><ref name="LR15"/> while Roche independently held a press conference from his hotel and answered questions.<ref name="LR15"/> Carrera Jeans-Vagabond manager David Boifava ordered Roche and Visentini to stay silent.<ref name="ep 15rv"/> The following day, many Italian newspapers called Roche a betrayer or cheat for his actions.<ref name="BRI 87"/><ref name="ISXIX"/><ref name="LR15">{{cite news|author=Mario Fossati|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1987/06/07/ma-il-colpevole-non-roche.html|title=Ma Il Colpevole Non e' Roche |language=Italian|date=7 June 1987|newspaper=La Repubblica|publisher=Gruppo Editoriale L'Espresso|accessdate=27 May 2012|trans_title=But Not The Culprit Roche|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QYkINfBv|archivedate=17 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=27}}<ref name="BBC">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/cycling/27323690|title=Giro d'Italia 2014: Roche's mixed memories of 1987 win|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=8 May 2014|accessdate=17 May 2014|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6QYjSrGpB|archivedate=18 June 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> Despite Visentini's statement, both riders started the sixteenth stage after receiving orders from Carrera company boss Tito Tachella.<ref name="BRI 87"/>{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=27}} In the days that followed, Italian fans threw things and spat at Roche, which led him to receive police protection until the race's conclusion.<ref name="BRI 87"/>{{sfn|Roche|2011|p=27}}<ref name="BBC"/> Looking back on the incident, Roche claimed that he just descended the mountain quicker than Visentini and did nothing wrong,<ref name="LR15"/><ref name="BBC"/> while Visentini maintained that Roche attacked him when he should have been aiding him.<ref name="ISXIX"/> Visentini accused Roche of dashing the team's morale and strategy,<ref name="LR15"/> but some critics believed that Roche's actions were acceptable because he was the stronger rider.<ref name="ISXIX"/><ref name="LRFin2"/>

